00:26:20,287 --> 00:26:23,414
were displayed on the seventh floor
of the Sogo department store.

234
00:26:24,124 --> 00:26:25,833
He wrote...

235
00:26:26,126 --> 00:26:30,088
"It's curiosity, of course, but also
a hint of industrial espionage.

236
00:26:30,923 --> 00:26:32,924
I imagine them bringing out
in two years

237
00:26:33,092 --> 00:26:36,177
a more efficient and less expensive
version of Catholicism.

238
00:26:37,304 --> 00:26:39,889
But there's also the fascination
associated with the sacred,

239
00:26:40,015 --> 00:26:41,975
even when it's someone else's.

240
00:27:23,475 --> 00:27:28,521
So when will French department stores
exhibit relics sacred to the Japanese

241
00:27:28,689 --> 00:27:31,858
such as can be seen at Jozankei,
on the island of Hokkaido?

242
00:27:32,359 --> 00:27:36,321
At first, one smiles at this combination
museum, chapel and sex shop.

243
00:27:36,822 --> 00:27:40,450
As always in Japan, one admires
how the walls between realms are so thin

244
00:27:40,576 --> 00:27:43,161
that one can in the same breath
contemplate a statue,

245
00:27:43,329 --> 00:27:45,079
buy an inflatable doll

246
00:27:45,247 --> 00:27:47,749
and give the goddess of fertility
the small offering

247
00:27:47,875 --> 00:27:50,251
that always accompanies
her displays,

248
00:27:50,377 --> 00:27:54,047
displays whose frankness would render
television's stratagems incomprehensible

249
00:27:54,465 --> 00:27:59,719
but for the fact that sex organs may
only be shown severed from the body.

250
00:28:12,191 --> 00:28:14,275
One would like to
believe in a world before the fall,

251
00:28:14,443 --> 00:28:16,527
inaccessible to the complications
of a puritanism

252
00:28:16,695 --> 00:28:20,365
whose phony shadow was imposed
on it by American occupation,

253
00:28:20,657 --> 00:28:23,326
where people who gather laughing
around the votive fountain,

254
00:28:23,452 --> 00:28:25,453
the woman who touches it
with a friendly gesture,

255
00:28:25,621 --> 00:28:28,581
share in the same cosmic innocence.

256
00:28:29,291 --> 00:28:31,876
The second part of the museum,
with its pairs of coupling animals,

257
00:28:32,044 --> 00:28:34,879
would then be the earthly paradise
as we've always dreamed of it.

258
00:28:35,047 --> 00:28:36,381
Not so sure.

259
00:28:36,548 --> 00:28:39,926
Animal innocence may be a trick
for getting around censorship,

260
00:28:40,386 --> 00:28:43,596
but perhaps also the mirror
of an impossible reconciliation,

261
00:28:43,722 --> 00:28:48,601
and even without original sin, this
earthly paradise may be a paradise lost.

262
00:28:51,188 --> 00:28:53,689
In the glossy splendor
of the gentle animals of Jozankei,

263
00:28:53,816 --> 00:28:56,859
I read the fundamental rift
of Japanese society,

264
00:28:56,985 --> 00:28:59,612
the rift that separates
men from women.

265
00:28:59,780 --> 00:29:02,573
In life it seems to manifest
in just two ways:

266
00:29:02,741 --> 00:29:04,450
violent slaughter,

267
00:29:04,576 --> 00:29:07,495
or a discreet melancholy
resembling Shonagon's,

268
00:29:07,621 --> 00:29:11,833
which the Japanese express
in a single - and untranslatable - word.

269
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:13,918
Bringing man down
to the level of the beasts

270
00:29:14,086 --> 00:29:16,129
against which
the church fathers inveighed

271
00:29:16,296 --> 00:29:19,715
becomes here the challenge of the beasts
to the 'poignancy of things,'

272
00:29:19,883 --> 00:29:22,218
to a melancholy whose tone
I can convey

273
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:25,388
by copying a few lines
from Samura Koichi:

274
00:29:27,224 --> 00:29:30,268
'Who said that time
heals all wounds?

275
00:29:31,270 --> 00:29:35,273
Better to say that time heals
everything except wounds.

276
00:29:35,524 --> 00:29:39,235
With time, the hurt of separation
loses its real limits.

277
00:29:39,361 --> 00:29:42,780
With time, the desired body
will soon disappear,

278
00:29:42,948 --> 00:29:45,992
and if the desiring body has already
ceased to exist for the other,

279
00:29:46,118 --> 00:29:49,954
then what remains
is a disembodied wound."'

280
00:29:57,671 --> 00:29:59,797
He wrote
that the Japanese secret -

281
00:29:59,965 --> 00:30:03,092
what Levi-Strauss called
the poignancy of things -

282
00:30:03,260 --> 00:30:05,803
implied the faculty
of communing with things,

283
00:30:05,971 --> 00:30:09,557
of entering into them,
of being them for a moment.

284
00:30:09,683 --> 00:30:12,310
It's only natural that, in their turn,
they should be like us -

285
00:30:12,436 --> 00:30:14,312
perishable and immortal.

286
00:30:21,570 --> 00:30:24,780
He wrote, "Animism is
a familiar notion in Africa.

287
00:30:24,948 --> 00:30:26,991
It's less often applied to Japan.

288
00:30:27,159 --> 00:30:29,118
What then shall we call
this diffuse belief

289
00:30:29,286 --> 00:30:33,331
according to which every fragment
of creation has its invisible counterpart?

290
00:30:33,790 --> 00:30:36,334
Building a factory or skyscraper

291
00:30:36,460 --> 00:30:39,670
begins with a ceremony to appease
the god who owns the land.

292
00:30:39,838 --> 00:30:43,841
There's a ceremony for brushes,
abacuses, even rusty needles.

293
00:30:44,009 --> 00:30:48,721
There's one on September 25th for
the repose of the soul of broken dolls.

294
00:30:48,847 --> 00:30:51,849
The dolls are piled up
in the Temple of Kiyomizu -

295
00:30:51,975 --> 00:30:56,771
which is consecrated to Kannon,
the goddess of compassion -

296
00:30:56,897 --> 00:30:59,023
and then burned in public.

297
00:31:34,851 --> 00:31:36,727
I watched the participants.

298
00:31:37,062 --> 00:31:39,230
I think the people who saw off
the kamikaze pilots

299
00:31:39,648 --> 00:31:42,066
had the same look on their faces."

300
00:32:14,850 --> 00:32:16,934
He wrote that the pictures
of Guinea-Bissau

301
00:32:17,102 --> 00:32:19,562
ought to be accompanied
by music from the Cape Verde Islands.

302
00:32:19,730 --> 00:32:22,773
That would be our contribution
to the unity dreamed of by Amílcar Cabral.

303
00:32:27,779 --> 00:32:31,949
"Why should a country so small
and so poor interest the world?

304
00:32:32,075 --> 00:32:34,076
They did what they could.

305
00:32:34,202 --> 00:32:37,622
They chased Portugal out,
so traumatizing its army

306
00:32:37,789 --> 00:32:40,249
that it moved to overthrow
its own dictatorship

307
00:32:40,417 --> 00:32:43,002
and led one briefly to believe
in a new revolution in Europe.

308
00:32:43,170 --> 00:32:44,879
Who remembers all that?

309
00:32:45,047 --> 00:32:47,965
History throws its empty bottles
out the window.

310
00:32:52,012 --> 00:32:54,388
This morning I was
on the dock at Pidjiguiti,

311
00:32:54,514 --> 00:32:56,515
where everything began in 1959,

312
00:32:56,642 --> 00:32:59,143
when the first victims
of the struggle were killed.

313
00:32:59,269 --> 00:33:02,438
It may be as difficult
to recognize Africa in this leaden fog

314
00:33:02,564 --> 00:33:04,607
as it is to recognize the struggle

315
00:33:04,775 --> 00:33:07,068
in the rather dull activity
of tropical longshoremen.

316
00:33:07,319 --> 00:33:09,278
Rumor has it
that every third-world leader

317
00:33:09,446 --> 00:33:11,822
coined the same phrase
the morning after independence:

318
00:33:11,948 --> 00:33:14,659
'Now the real problems begin.'

319
00:33:14,826 --> 00:33:18,037
Cabral never got a chance to say it.
He was assassinated first.

320
00:33:18,163 --> 00:33:21,666
But the problems began,
and went on, and are still going on.

321
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:24,543
Rather unexciting problems
for revolutionary romanticism:

322
00:33:24,711 --> 00:33:27,213
to work, to produce, to distribute,

323
00:33:27,381 --> 00:33:29,674
to overcome postwar exhaustion

324
00:33:29,841 --> 00:33:32,510
and the temptations
of power and privilege.

325
00:33:32,678 --> 00:33:36,847
But after all, history's only bitter
to those who expect a sugar coating.

326
00:33:54,366 --> 00:33:57,827
My personal problem
was more specific:

327
00:33:57,953 --> 00:34:00,037
How to film the ladies of Bissau?

328
00:34:00,205 --> 00:34:03,207
Apparently, the eye's magical function
was working against me there.

329
00:34:03,834 --> 00:34:05,960
In the marketplaces
of Bissau and Cape Verde,

330
00:34:06,086 --> 00:34:08,087
I again encountered
those egalitarian stares

331
00:34:08,213 --> 00:34:12,133
and this sequence of glances
that bordered on seduction.

332
00:34:12,968 --> 00:34:14,760
I see her.

333
00:34:15,595 --> 00:34:17,430
She sees me.

334
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:19,890
She knows I see her.

335
00:34:22,561 --> 00:34:24,270
She glances my way,

336
00:34:24,396 --> 00:34:27,857
but furtively, as if I'm not
really the object of her gaze.

337
00:34:27,983 --> 00:34:30,401
Finally, the direct gaze

338
00:34:31,570 --> 00:34:35,239
lasting 1 /24th of a second,
the length of a film frame.

339
00:34:41,079 --> 00:34:44,832
All women have a built-in
kernel of indestructibility,

340
00:34:45,041 --> 00:34:48,127
and men's task has always been
to keep them from realizing it

341
00:34:48,295 --> 00:34:50,087
for as long as possible.

342
00:34:50,213 --> 00:34:54,550
African men are just as good
at this task as others,

343
00:34:54,676 --> 00:34:59,180
but after a close look at African women,
I wouldn't necessarily bet on the men."

344
00:36:50,750 --> 00:36:53,419
He told me the story
of Hachiko the dog.

345
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:56,213
"A dog waited for his master
every day at the station.

346
00:36:56,339 --> 00:36:59,216
The master died,
but the dog didn't know it,

347
00:36:59,384 --> 00:37:02,052
and he continued to wait,
all his life.

348
00:37:02,220 --> 00:37:04,930
People were moved
and brought him food.

349
00:37:05,098 --> 00:37:09,560
They still place sushi and rice cakes
before the statue erected in his honor

350
00:37:09,728 --> 00:37:13,147
so that the faithful soul of Hachiko
will never go hungry.

351
00:37:18,612 --> 00:37:22,531
Tokyo is full of these small legends
and animal intercessors.

352
00:37:22,949 --> 00:37:26,911
The Mitsukoshi lion stands guard over
what was once the empire of Mr. Okada,

353
00:37:27,078 --> 00:37:29,121
a great collector of French paintings,

354
00:37:29,289 --> 00:37:31,206
the man who rented
the Château of Versailles

355
00:37:31,374 --> 00:37:33,876
to celebrate the 1 00th anniversary
of his department stores.

356
00:37:34,002 --> 00:37:36,253
In the computer section
of one such store,

357
00:37:36,421 --> 00:37:38,505
I've seen young Japanese
exercising their brain muscles

358
00:37:38,673 --> 00:37:41,216
like young Athenians at the palestra.

359
00:37:42,427 --> 00:37:44,428
They have a war to win.

360
00:37:44,596 --> 00:37:47,806
History books of the future will perhaps
rank the battle of the integrated circuit

361
00:37:47,974 --> 00:37:50,184
with the battles
of Salamis or Agincourt.

362
00:37:54,105 --> 00:37:58,025
But they honor the unfortunate
adversary by leaving other fields to him:

363
00:37:58,151 --> 00:38:01,779
men's fashions this season are placed
under the sign of John Kennedy."

364
00:38:40,902 --> 00:38:43,529
Like an old votive turtle
stationed in the corner of a field,

365
00:38:43,697 --> 00:38:47,950
Mr. Akao, president
of the Japanese Patriotic Party,

366
00:38:48,118 --> 00:38:52,413
rails from his rolling balcony
against the international communist plot.

367
00:38:53,665 --> 00:38:55,165
He wrote...

368
00:38:56,710 --> 00:38:59,378
"The extreme right's vans,
with their flags and megaphones,

369
00:38:59,546 --> 00:39:01,338
are part of the Tokyo landscape.

370
00:39:01,840 --> 00:39:04,216
Mr. Akao is their focal point.

371
00:39:04,342 --> 00:39:07,011
I think he'll have his own statue,
like Ηachiko the dog,

372
00:39:07,178 --> 00:39:11,890
at this intersection that he leaves
only to go prophesy on the battlefields.

373
00:39:17,605 --> 00:39:21,316
He was at Narita in the '60s:

374
00:39:21,443 --> 00:39:24,528
Peasants fought an airport
to be built on their land,

375
00:39:24,654 --> 00:39:28,615
with Mr. Akao denouncing Moscow's
hand in everything that moved.

376
00:39:30,201 --> 00:39:33,078
Yurakucho is
Tokyo's political arena.

377
00:39:33,204 --> 00:39:36,040
I once saw a monk there
pray for peace in Vietnam.

378
00:39:37,542 --> 00:39:39,626
Today, young right-wing activists

379
00:39:39,753 --> 00:39:43,672
protest the annexation
of the northern islands by the Russians.

380
00:39:43,798 --> 00:39:46,341
Sometimes they're told that
Japan's commercial relations

381
00:39:46,509 --> 00:39:48,469
with the abominable occupier
to the north

382
00:39:48,636 --> 00:39:50,804
are a thousand times better
than with the American ally,

383
00:39:50,972 --> 00:39:53,724
who's always whining
about economic aggression.

384
00:39:53,892 --> 00:39:55,934
Nothing is simple.

385
00:40:01,357 --> 00:40:04,234
On the other sidewalk,
the left has the floor.

386
00:40:04,861 --> 00:40:07,529
Korean Catholic opposition
leader Kim Dae Jung,

387
00:40:07,697 --> 00:40:10,699
kidnapped in Tokyo in '73
by the South Korean Gestapo,

388
00:40:11,034 --> 00:40:13,535
is threatened
with a death sentence.

389
00:40:13,870 --> 00:40:15,871
A group has begun a hunger strike.

390
00:40:16,039 --> 00:40:19,249
Some very young activists
gather signatures in his support.

391
00:41:02,544 --> 00:41:05,629
I returned to Narita for the birthday
of one of the victims of the struggle.

392
00:41:07,632 --> 00:41:09,508
The demonstration was unreal.

393
00:41:09,676 --> 00:41:11,885
I felt like I was in Brigadoon,

394
00:41:12,053 --> 00:41:14,972
like I'd woken up ten years later
amid the same actors,

395
00:41:15,140 --> 00:41:18,976
the same blue-suited police
and helmeted adolescents,

396
00:41:19,144 --> 00:41:21,478
the same slogan,
the same banners...

397
00:41:22,480 --> 00:41:25,649
and the same goal:
to fight the airport.

398
00:41:25,942 --> 00:41:29,653
Just one thing has been added:
the airport itself.

399
00:41:29,821 --> 00:41:32,114
But its single runway
hemmed in by barbed wire

400
00:41:32,282 --> 00:41:34,825
looks more besieged than victorious.

401
00:41:51,593 --> 00:41:56,180
My pal Hayao Yamaneko
has found a solution:

402
00:41:56,306 --> 00:42:00,017
If the images of the present don't change,
change the images of the past.

403
00:42:00,518 --> 00:42:04,104
He showed me clashes of the '60s
run through his synthesizer.

404
00:42:04,856 --> 00:42:07,900
'Less deceptive pictures,' he says,
with the conviction of a fanatic,

405
00:42:08,067 --> 00:42:10,194
than those you see on television.'

406
00:42:10,361 --> 00:42:13,572
At least they proclaim themselves
to be what they are: images -

407
00:42:13,698 --> 00:42:18,202
not the portable and compact form
of an already inaccessible reality.

408
00:42:20,455 --> 00:42:23,457
Hayao calls
his machine's world 'the Zone,'

409
00:42:23,583 --> 00:42:25,709
in an homage to Tarkovsky.

410
00:43:15,134 --> 00:43:19,137
What Narita brought back to me
like a shattered hologram

411
00:43:19,305 --> 00:43:21,556
was a fragment
of the '60s generation.

412
00:43:23,851 --> 00:43:27,312
If to love without illusions is still
to love, I can say that I loved it.

413
00:43:27,772 --> 00:43:29,606
It was a generation
that often exasperated me,

414
00:43:29,774 --> 00:43:32,609
for I didn't share its utopian goal
of uniting in a common struggle

415
00:43:32,777 --> 00:43:36,655
those who revolt against poverty
and those who revolt against wealth,

416
00:43:36,823 --> 00:43:41,785
but it let out a primordial scream that
better-adjusted voices no longer could.

417
00:43:49,460 --> 00:43:52,504
I met peasants there who'd come
to know themselves through the struggle.

418
00:43:52,672 --> 00:43:54,673
In concrete terms, it had failed.

419
00:43:54,841 --> 00:43:57,592
Yet all they had won
in their understanding of the world

420
00:43:57,719 --> 00:43:59,511
and of themselves

421
00:43:59,637 --> 00:44:02,764
could only have been won
through the struggle.

422
00:44:03,474 --> 00:44:07,185
As for the students, some massacred
each other in the mountains

423
00:44:07,312 --> 00:44:09,271
in the name
of revolutionary purity,

424
00:44:09,439 --> 00:44:12,316
while others had studied capitalism
so thoroughly to fight it

425
00:44:12,483 --> 00:44:15,235
that they now provide it
with its best executives.

426
00:44:15,403 --> 00:44:18,530
Like everywhere else, the movement
had its posturers and its careerists -

427
00:44:18,698 --> 00:44:21,992
including those who made
a career of martyrdom -

428
00:44:22,160 --> 00:44:24,828
but it carried with it all those
who said, like Che Guevara,

429
00:44:24,996 --> 00:44:28,999
that they 'trembled with indignation
at every injustice committed in the world.'

430
00:44:29,834 --> 00:44:32,627
They wanted to give
a political meaning to their generosity,

431
00:44:32,795 --> 00:44:36,131
and their generosity
has outlasted their politics.

432
00:44:36,257 --> 00:44:41,762
That's why I will never allow it to be
said that youth is wasted on the young."

433
00:44:59,322 --> 00:45:01,907
"The youth who gather
every weekend at Shinjuku

434
00:45:02,033 --> 00:45:05,202
obviously know they're not
on a launching pad toward real life,

435
00:45:05,328 --> 00:45:08,038
that they are life, to be eaten
on the spot, like fresh donuts.

436
00:45:10,041 --> 00:45:11,583
It's a very simple secret.

437
00:45:11,709 --> 00:45:15,170
The old try to hide it,
and not all the young know it.

438
00:45:15,296 --> 00:45:17,672
The 10-year-old girl
who tied her friend's hands

439
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:20,050
and threw her from the 13th floor

440
00:45:20,218 --> 00:45:23,678
for speaking badly of their class team
hadn't discovered it yet.

441
00:45:23,805 --> 00:45:26,598
Parents who demand
more special telephone lines

442
00:45:26,766 --> 00:45:28,558
to prevent children's suicides

443
00:45:28,726 --> 00:45:32,562
find out a little late
that they kept the secret too well.

444
00:45:33,856 --> 00:45:37,317
Rock is an international language
for spreading the secret.

445
00:45:37,902 --> 00:45:40,695
Another is peculiar to Tokyo.

446
00:45:48,871 --> 00:45:52,124
For the Takenoko,
