447
00:45:52,250 --> 00:45:54,084
They are baby Martians.

448
00:45:54,210 --> 00:45:57,546
I go see them dance
every Sunday in Yoyogi Park.

449
00:45:57,964 --> 00:46:02,134
They want people to look at them
but seem not to notice when they do.

450
00:46:02,301 --> 00:46:03,927
They live
in a parallel time stream.

451
00:46:04,095 --> 00:46:07,389
An invisible aquarium wall
separates them from their audience,

452
00:46:07,515 --> 00:46:09,766
and I can spend a whole afternoon

453
00:46:09,934 --> 00:46:14,104
watching a little Takenoko girl
learn the customs of her planet.

454
00:46:28,035 --> 00:46:30,287
Beyond that, they wear dog tags,

455
00:46:30,413 --> 00:46:33,165
they obey a whistle,
the Mafia extorts money from them,

456
00:46:35,835 --> 00:46:38,295
a boy is always in charge."

457
00:47:36,604 --> 00:47:38,522
One day he writes to me,

458
00:47:38,689 --> 00:47:40,440
"Description of a dream:

459
00:47:40,608 --> 00:47:42,692
More and more,
my dreams are set

460
00:47:42,860 --> 00:47:44,653
in the department stores of Tokyo,

461
00:47:44,820 --> 00:47:47,280
the subterranean passages
that parallel the city above.

462
00:47:49,242 --> 00:47:52,869
A face appears, then disappears.
A trace is found, then lost.

463
00:47:53,037 --> 00:47:56,206
The folklore of dreams is so much intact
that the next day, when I'm awake,

464
00:47:56,332 --> 00:47:59,543
I realize that I continue to seek
in this basement labyrinth

465
00:47:59,669 --> 00:48:02,712
the presence concealed
the night before.

466
00:48:03,172 --> 00:48:05,715
I begin to wonder
if those dreams are really mine,

467
00:48:05,841 --> 00:48:09,761
or if they're part of a totality,
a gigantic collective dream,

468
00:48:09,929 --> 00:48:13,098
of which the entire city
may be the projection.

469
00:48:13,558 --> 00:48:16,393
It might suffice to pick up
any of the telephones lying around

470
00:48:16,561 --> 00:48:18,311
to hear a familiar voice

471
00:48:19,063 --> 00:48:21,940
or the beating of a heart -

472
00:48:22,400 --> 00:48:25,068
Sei Shonagon's, for example.

473
00:48:25,945 --> 00:48:27,612
All the underground passages
lead to train stations.

474
00:48:27,780 --> 00:48:30,949
The same companies own the stores
and the railroads that bear their name -

475
00:48:31,117 --> 00:48:34,411
Keio, Odakyu,
all those names of ports.

476
00:48:34,537 --> 00:48:37,789
The train inhabited by sleeping people
assembles all the fragments of dreams

477
00:48:37,915 --> 00:48:41,167
and makes a single film of them,
the ultimate film.

478
00:48:41,294 --> 00:48:44,546
The tickets from the automatic dispenser
grant admission to the show."

479
00:53:50,269 --> 00:53:53,855
He told me of the January light
on the stations' stairways.

480
00:53:54,398 --> 00:53:57,734
Ηe said the city ought to be
deciphered like a musical score.

481
00:53:59,820 --> 00:54:03,573
One could get lost in the great orchestral
masses and the accumulation of details,

482
00:54:03,741 --> 00:54:05,950
but that yielded
the cheapest image of Tokyo:

483
00:54:06,118 --> 00:54:08,828
overcrowded,
megalomaniac, inhuman.

484
00:54:08,996 --> 00:54:11,456
Ηe thought he saw
more subtle cycles there:

485
00:54:11,624 --> 00:54:14,375
rhythms, clusters of faces
glimpsed in passing,

486
00:54:14,501 --> 00:54:18,212
as different and precise
as groups of instruments.

487
00:54:18,589 --> 00:54:21,633
Sometimes the musical comparison
coincided with plain reality:

488
00:54:22,217 --> 00:54:25,845
The Sony stairway in the Ginza
was itself a musical instrument,

489
00:54:25,971 --> 00:54:28,097
each step a note.

490
00:54:28,265 --> 00:54:31,267
It all fit together like voices
in a complicated fugue,

491
00:54:31,393 --> 00:54:34,395
but it was enough to seize one
and hang on to it:

492
00:54:34,521 --> 00:54:36,940
the television screens,
for example.

493
00:54:37,107 --> 00:54:39,192
All by themselves
they created an itinerary

494
00:54:39,318 --> 00:54:42,111
that sometimes
took unexpected turns.

495
00:54:42,237 --> 00:54:43,863
It was sumo season,

496
00:54:43,989 --> 00:54:47,283
and the fans watching the fights
in the very chic Ginza showrooms

497
00:54:47,451 --> 00:54:50,203
were the poorest of the Tokyo poor,

498
00:54:50,329 --> 00:54:52,872
so poor they didn't have even a TV set.

499
00:54:53,040 --> 00:54:56,125
Ηe saw them come,
these lost souls of Namidabashi

500
00:54:56,293 --> 00:54:59,671
with whom he'd drunk sake
one sunny dawn.

501
00:54:59,797 --> 00:55:02,465
How many seasons ago was that now?

502
00:56:33,015 --> 00:56:34,891
He wrote me...

503
00:56:36,101 --> 00:56:38,436
"Even in the stalls
selling spare electronic parts

504
00:56:38,604 --> 00:56:41,355
that some hipsters use for jewelry,

505
00:56:41,523 --> 00:56:44,692
there is, in Tokyo's musical score,
a particular staff

506
00:56:44,860 --> 00:56:48,362
whose rarity in Europe condemns me
to a real acoustic exile:

507
00:56:48,530 --> 00:56:51,157
the music of video games.

508
00:56:51,742 --> 00:56:53,743
They're built into tables.

509
00:56:53,911 --> 00:56:56,829
You can drink and have lunch
and go on playing.

510
00:56:57,081 --> 00:56:58,998
The arcades open onto the street,

511
00:56:59,166 --> 00:57:01,793
where you can listen
and play from memory.

512
00:57:30,697 --> 00:57:33,032
I witnessed the birth
of these games in Japan.

513
00:57:33,200 --> 00:57:37,120
I met them again later all over the world,
but one detail was different.

514
00:57:37,246 --> 00:57:38,996
At first it was the familiar game,

515
00:57:39,164 --> 00:57:42,708
a politically incorrect battering
aimed at killing off creatures

516
00:57:42,876 --> 00:57:47,630
that were either prairie dogs
or baby seals - I can't be sure which.

517
00:57:48,632 --> 00:57:51,467
Here's the new Japanese variation:

518
00:57:51,635 --> 00:57:55,763
lnstead of the critters, there are
vaguely human heads identified by labels.

519
00:57:55,889 --> 00:57:58,641
At the top, the chairman of the board.

520
00:57:58,892 --> 00:58:02,603
In front of him,
the vice president and directors.

521
00:58:02,729 --> 00:58:05,982
In the front row, department heads
and personnel manager.

522
00:58:06,400 --> 00:58:08,442
The guy I filmed,

523
00:58:08,569 --> 00:58:11,279
who was smashing up
the hierarchy with enviable energy,

524
00:58:11,405 --> 00:58:13,948
confided that it was
not at all allegorical for him,

525
00:58:14,116 --> 00:58:16,701
that he was thinking
very specifically of his superiors.

526
00:58:16,869 --> 00:58:19,162
That's no doubt why
the 'personnel manager'

527
00:58:19,288 --> 00:58:23,541
has been clubbed so often and so hard
that it was taken out of commission

528
00:58:23,709 --> 00:58:27,378
and a baby seal
reinserted in its place.

529
00:58:32,217 --> 00:58:34,677
Hayao Yamaneko invents
video games with his machine.

530
00:58:36,096 --> 00:58:39,515
To please me, he puts in
my most beloved animals,

531
00:58:39,683 --> 00:58:41,684
the cat and the owl.

532
00:58:48,233 --> 00:58:50,359
He claims that only electronics

533
00:58:50,485 --> 00:58:55,031
can deal with feeling,
memory and imagination.

534
00:58:56,325 --> 00:58:58,659
Mizoguchi's Arsène Lupin,
for example,

535
00:58:58,827 --> 00:59:01,746
or the no-less-imaginary
Burakumin.

536
00:59:02,414 --> 00:59:06,959
Ηow to show a category
of Japanese that doesn't exist?

537
00:59:07,377 --> 00:59:11,672
Yes, I saw them in Osaka, for hire
by the day, sleeping on the ground.

538
00:59:11,798 --> 00:59:14,926
Since the Middle Ages they've been
doomed to grubby and thankless jobs,

539
00:59:15,052 --> 00:59:18,429
but since the Meiji era,
officially nothing sets them apart,

540
00:59:18,555 --> 00:59:23,059
and their real name - the eta -
is a taboo word, not to be pronounced.

541
00:59:24,269 --> 00:59:26,020
They are non-persons.

542
00:59:26,146 --> 00:59:28,981
How can they be shown,
except as non-images?

543
00:59:38,200 --> 00:59:42,578
Video games are the first stage in a plan
for machines to help the human race,

544
00:59:42,746 --> 00:59:45,373
the only plan that offers
a future for intelligence.

545
00:59:46,792 --> 00:59:49,877
For the moment, the unsurpassable
philosophy of our time

546
00:59:50,003 --> 00:59:52,004
is found in Pac-Man.

547
00:59:52,923 --> 00:59:55,591
I didn't know, while sacrificing
my 100-yen coins to him,

548
00:59:55,759 --> 00:59:57,969
that he was to conquer the world.

549
00:59:58,136 --> 01:00:01,889
Perhaps because he's the most perfect
graphic metaphor of the human condition.

550
01:00:02,057 --> 01:00:03,975
He puts into true perspective

551
01:00:04,142 --> 01:00:06,435
the balance of power between
the individual and the environment,

552
01:00:06,603 --> 01:00:08,813
and he tells us soberly
that though there's honor

553
01:00:08,939 --> 01:00:11,274
in carrying out the greatest number
of victorious attacks,

554
01:00:11,400 --> 01:00:14,443
it never amounts
to anything in the end."

555
01:00:57,321 --> 01:00:59,613
He was pleased to see
the same chrysanthemums

556
01:00:59,781 --> 01:01:02,658
at funerals
for both men and animals.

557
01:01:02,784 --> 01:01:05,786
He described the ceremony
held at the zoo in Ueno,

558
01:01:05,912 --> 01:01:08,122
in memory of animals
that had died during the year.

559
01:01:08,749 --> 01:01:10,249
"For two years now,

560
01:01:10,417 --> 01:01:13,711
a certain panda's death has rendered
this day even more sorrowful,

561
01:01:13,837 --> 01:01:15,796
a loss more irreparable,
say the newspapers,

562
01:01:15,964 --> 01:01:17,757
than the recent death
of the prime minister.

563
01:01:17,924 --> 01:01:19,800
Last year people really cried.

564
01:01:19,926 --> 01:01:21,719
Now they seem to be
getting used to it,

565
01:01:21,887 --> 01:01:24,013
accepting that each year
death takes a panda

566
01:01:24,181 --> 01:01:27,016
as dragons carry off
young girls in fairy tales.

567
01:01:29,311 --> 01:01:31,479
I've heard this sentence:

568
01:01:33,023 --> 01:01:35,024
'The partition separating
life from death

569
01:01:35,192 --> 01:01:38,736
doesn't seem as thick to us
as it does to a Westerner.'

570
01:01:41,114 --> 01:01:44,950
What I've read most often in the eyes
of people about to die is surprise.

571
01:01:45,660 --> 01:01:49,955
What I read right now in the eyes
of Japanese children is curiosity,

572
01:01:50,082 --> 01:01:53,834
as if they were trying
to see through the partition

573
01:01:54,002 --> 01:01:56,045
to understand an animal's death."

574
01:03:19,296 --> 01:03:21,130
"I've returned from a country

575
01:03:21,298 --> 01:03:25,134
where death is not a partition
to cross but a road to follow.

576
01:03:25,844 --> 01:03:28,262
The Great Ancestor
of the Bijago archipelago

577
01:03:28,430 --> 01:03:30,556
has described for us
the itinerary of the dead,

578
01:03:30,682 --> 01:03:34,727
and how they move from island to island
according to a rigorous protocol,

579
01:03:34,895 --> 01:03:36,896
until they come to the last beach,

580
01:03:37,022 --> 01:03:39,815
where they wait
for the ship to the other world.

581
01:03:41,860 --> 01:03:45,446
If by accident one should meet them,
it is imperative not to recognize them.

582
01:03:48,950 --> 01:03:51,660
The Bijagos
are part of Guinea-Bissau.

583
01:03:51,828 --> 01:03:55,789
In an old film clip, Amílcar Cabral
waves good-bye to the shore.

584
01:03:55,957 --> 01:03:59,126
He's right.
Ηe'll never see it again.

585
01:03:59,461 --> 01:04:01,921
Luís Cabral made
the same gesture 1 5 years later,

586
01:04:02,088 --> 01:04:04,673
on the canoe
that was bringing us back.

587
01:04:04,841 --> 01:04:09,345
Guinea had by that time become a nation,
and Luís was its president.

588
01:04:09,846 --> 01:04:12,806
All those who remember the war
remember him.

589
01:04:13,183 --> 01:04:17,686
Like his half brother Amílcar, he was of mixed
Guinean and Cape Verdian blood,

590
01:04:17,854 --> 01:04:22,233
and, like Amílcar, a founding member
of an unusual party, the PAIGC,

591
01:04:22,400 --> 01:04:25,361
which, by uniting the two colonized
countries in a single struggle,

592
01:04:25,529 --> 01:04:28,822
sought to herald
a federation of the two states.

593
01:04:29,741 --> 01:04:32,117
I've heard the stories
of former guerrilla fighters,

594
01:04:32,285 --> 01:04:36,205
who'd fought in conditions so inhuman
that they pitied the Portuguese soldiers

595
01:04:36,373 --> 01:04:38,582
for having to bear what
they themselves suffered.

596
01:04:38,750 --> 01:04:41,293
I heard that
and many more things

597
01:04:41,461 --> 01:04:45,297
that make one ashamed for having used
lightly, even if inadvertently,

598
01:04:45,465 --> 01:04:48,926
the word "guerrilla" to describe
a certain kind of filmmaking,

599
01:04:49,094 --> 01:04:51,512
a word linked at the time
to many theoretical debates

600
01:04:51,680 --> 01:04:54,265
as well as bloody defeats
on the ground.

601
01:04:54,432 --> 01:04:57,393
Amílcar Cabral was the only one
to lead a victorious guerrilla war,

602
01:04:57,561 --> 01:04:59,979
and not only in terms
of military conquests.

603
01:05:00,146 --> 01:05:02,565
He knew his people.
Ηe'd studied them at length.

604
01:05:02,732 --> 01:05:06,318
Ηe wanted every liberated region
to herald a different kind of society.

605
01:05:06,486 --> 01:05:09,113
The socialist countries send
weapons to arm the fighters.

606
01:05:09,281 --> 01:05:12,449
The social democracies
fill the people's stores.

607
01:05:12,617 --> 01:05:15,077
May the extreme Left
forgive history,

608
01:05:15,245 --> 01:05:20,082
but if the guerrillas are like fish
in water, it's a bit thanks to Sweden.

609
01:05:20,250 --> 01:05:23,794
Amílcar was not afraid of ambiguities.
He knew the traps.

610
01:05:23,962 --> 01:05:25,879
He wrote...

611
01:05:26,006 --> 01:05:29,592
"It's as though
we're facing a raging river,

612
01:05:29,759 --> 01:05:31,635
and those trying
to cross are drowning.

613
01:05:31,803 --> 01:05:34,555
But there's no choice.
They must get to the other side."

614
01:05:53,742 --> 01:05:57,536
Now the scene moves to Cassaca,
February 17th, 1980,

615
01:05:57,704 --> 01:06:00,956
but to grasp it properly,
one must move forward in time:

616
01:06:01,124 --> 01:06:04,501
In a year, Luís Cabral,
the president, will be in prison,

617
01:06:04,628 --> 01:06:07,921
and the weeping man
he has just decorated, Major Nino,

618
01:06:08,089 --> 01:06:10,007
will have taken power.

619
01:06:10,133 --> 01:06:12,092
The party will have split.

620
01:06:12,218 --> 01:06:15,804
Guineans and Capeverdians
will be fighting over Amílcar's legacy.

621
01:06:15,972 --> 01:06:18,682
We'll see that beneath
this ceremony of promotions,

622
01:06:18,808 --> 01:06:21,852
seemingly perpetuating
the brotherhood of the struggle,

623
01:06:22,020 --> 01:06:24,938
there lay a pit
of post-victory bitterness,

624
01:06:25,106 --> 01:06:28,275
and that Nino's tears expressed
not an ex-warrior's emotion

625
01:06:28,443 --> 01:06:30,319
but the wounded pride of a hero

626
01:06:30,487 --> 01:06:33,447
slighted at not being raised
high enough above the rest.

627
01:06:35,659 --> 01:06:38,619
Beneath each of these faces
lies a memory,

628
01:06:38,787 --> 01:06:41,955
and where there was to be
one collective memory,

629
01:06:42,207 --> 01:06:45,834
there are a thousand memories of men
who parade their personal wounds

630
01:06:46,002 --> 01:06:47,836
in the great wound of history.

631
01:06:49,130 --> 01:06:53,342
In Portugal, swept up in turn
by the breaking wave of Bissau,

632
01:06:53,468 --> 01:06:57,304
Miguel Torga, who'd struggled all his
life against the dictatorship, wrote,

633
01:06:57,430 --> 01:07:00,891
'Every bit player
represents only himself.

634
01:07:01,267 --> 01:07:03,519
lnstead of seeking social change,

635
01:07:03,687 --> 01:07:06,522
he seeks simply,
in the revolutionary act,

636
01:07:06,690 --> 01:07:09,525
to boost his own image.'

637
01:07:11,486 --> 01:07:14,238
That's the way
the breakers recede,

638
01:07:14,406 --> 01:07:18,575
and so predictably that one must believe
in an 'amnesia of the future'

639
01:07:18,743 --> 01:07:21,954
that history bestows,
out of mercy or self-interest,

640
01:07:22,122 --> 01:07:24,456
on those it recruits.

641
01:07:24,582 --> 01:07:28,127
Amílcar murdered
by members of his own party,

642
01:07:28,294 --> 01:07:31,714
the liberated areas
fallen to bloody petty tyrants,

643
01:07:31,881 --> 01:07:33,966
liquidated in their turn
by a central power

644
01:07:34,134 --> 01:07:37,720
to whose stability everyone
paid homage until the military coup -

645
01:07:37,887 --> 01:07:40,305
that's how history advances,

646
01:07:40,432 --> 01:07:43,559
plugging its memory
like one plugs one's ears.

647
01:07:43,727 --> 01:07:45,519
Luís, exiled to Cuba,

648
01:07:45,687 --> 01:07:48,397
and Nino,
himself a target of later plots,

649
01:07:48,565 --> 01:07:52,401
can summon each other endlessly
before history's court -

650
01:07:52,569 --> 01:07:54,653
but history doesn't care.

651
01:07:54,779 --> 01:07:58,073
It has only one friend,
the one Brando spoke of in Apocalypse:

652
01:07:58,533 --> 01:08:01,410
the horror that has
a name and a face.

653
01:08:03,788 --> 01:08:06,039
I'm writing you all this
from another world,

654
01:08:06,166 --> 01:08:08,333
a world of appearances.

655
01:08:08,460 --> 01:08:11,670
In a way, the two worlds
communicate with each other.

656
01:08:11,796 --> 01:08:14,548
Memory is to one
what history is to the other:

657
01:08:14,716 --> 01:08:16,717
an impossibility.

658
01:08:17,260 --> 01:08:20,429
Legends are born of the need
to decipher the indecipherable.

659
01:08:20,555 --> 01:08:23,265
Memories must make do
with their delirium, with their drift.

660
01:08:26,019 --> 01:08:27,936
A moment stopped would burn

661
01:08:28,104 --> 01:08:31,482
like a frame of film caught
in the furnace of the projector.

662
01:08:31,608 --> 01:08:34,443
Madness protects, as fever does.

663
01:08:36,279 --> 01:08:38,739
I envy Hayao and his Zone.

664
01:08:38,907 --> 01:08:41,283
He plays
with the signs of his memory.

665
01:08:41,451 --> 01:08:43,660
He pins them down
and decorates them like insects

666
01:08:43,828 --> 01:08:45,621
that have flown beyond time

667
01:08:45,789 --> 01:08:49,666
and that he can contemplate
from a point outside of time -

668
01:08:49,793 --> 01:08:52,252
the only eternity we have left.

669
01:08:53,213 --> 01:08:55,214
I look at his machines.

670
01:08:55,381 --> 01:08:59,593
I think of a world where each memory
could create its own legend."

671
01:10:03,700 --> 01:10:06,034
He wrote that only one film
had been capable

672
01:10:06,160 --> 01:10:08,287
of portraying impossible memory,
insane memory:

673
01:10:08,454 --> 01:10:11,373
Alfred Hitchcock's Vertigo.

674
01:10:13,251 --> 01:10:15,127
In the spiral of the opening titles,

675
01:10:15,253 --> 01:10:19,006
he saw time covering a field
growing ever wider as it moved away,

676
01:10:19,132 --> 01:10:23,594
a cyclone whose present moment
contains the motionless eye.

677
01:10:24,888 --> 01:10:28,932
In San Francisco he'd gone
on a pilgrimage to all the film's locations.

678
01:10:29,475 --> 01:10:31,560
The florist Podesta Baldocchi,

679
01:10:31,728 --> 01:10:34,813
where James Stewart
spies on Kim Novak,

680
01:10:34,939 --> 01:10:36,940
he the hunter and she the prey -

681
01:10:37,108 --> 01:10:39,443
or was it the other way around?

682
01:10:39,819 --> 01:10:42,738
The tile floor hadn't changed.

683
01:10:43,072 --> 01:10:45,782
He'd driven up and down
the hills of San Francisco,

684
01:10:45,909 --> 01:10:49,620
where Jimmy Stewart - Scottie -
follows Kim Novak - Madeleine.

685
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:55,751
It seems to be about pursuit,
mystery and murder,

686
01:10:55,919 --> 01:10:58,295
but in truth
it's about power and freedom,

687
01:10:58,463 --> 01:11:00,797
melancholy and dazzlement,

688
01:11:00,965 --> 01:11:05,093
so carefully coded within the spiral
that you could miss it

689
01:11:05,261 --> 01:11:07,679
and not immediately notice
that this vertigo of space

690
01:11:07,847 --> 01:11:10,849
in reality stands
for the vertigo of time.

691
01:11:12,560 --> 01:11:14,519
He'd followed every trail,

692
01:11:14,646 --> 01:11:16,730
even to the cemetery
at Mission Dolores,

693
01:11:16,856 --> 01:11:20,275
where Madeleine prayed
at the grave of a woman long dead

694
01:11:20,443 --> 01:11:22,945
whom she should not have known.

695
01:11:23,279 --> 01:11:25,781
He'd followed Madeleine -
as Scottie had done -

696
01:11:25,949 --> 01:11:27,824
to the Museum
of the Legion of Honor,

697
01:11:27,951 --> 01:11:31,078
before the portrait of a dead woman
she shouldn't have known.

698
01:11:31,245 --> 01:11:33,872
And on the portrait,
as in Madeleine's hair,

699
01:11:33,998 --> 01:11:36,041
the spiral of time.

